{
  "doc_id": "61468",
  "text": "Family studies have shown strong concordance for diabetic nephropathy (DN) risk in type 1 and type 2 diabetes [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . This suggests that DN risk, although related to glycaemia [6] , is substantially genetically determined [CITATION_6] 7, 8] . Skin fibroblast (SF) behaviours after multiple in vitro passages are associated with DN risk [9] [10] [11] . Moreover, sodium/hydrogen exchanger isoform 1 (NHE-1) activity [12] is concordant in type 1 diabetic sibling pairs who are concordant for DN lesions [13] .",
